15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
16 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
17 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 180.14 of Title 17, unless there
18 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
19 Sections 1 through 8 of this act shall be known and may be cited as
20 the "Oklahoma Energy Storage Resource Safety Act".
21 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 180.15 of Title 17, unless there
23 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24 The Legislature finds that:
Req. No. 17207 Page 3

1 1. To protect the citizens of Oklahoma, energy storage
2 resources shall satisfy safety codes and standards; and
3 2. This act is intended to help Oklahoma secure the benefits of
4 energy storage resources to provide electric grid reliability.
5 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
6 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 180.16 of Title 17, unless there
7 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
8 As used in the Oklahoma Energy Storage Resource Safety Act:
9 1. "Commencement of operations" means the date on which an
10 energy storage resource first delivers electricity to the grid in an
11 amount sufficient for commercial sale or use off-site from the
12 energy storage resource, but shall not include amounts of electrical
13 energy used only for the maintenance or testing of the energy
14 storage resource or related equipment;
15 2. "Energy storage resource" means a resource capable of
16 receiving electric energy from the electrical grid, or from a
17 generation source with which it is associated, and storing such
18 electric energy for later injection into the electrical grid;
19 3. "Energy storage resource agreement" means a lease agreement
20 between a grantee and a landowner that authorizes the grantee to
21 operate an energy storage resource on the leased property;
22 4. "Grantee" means a person, other than an electric utility
23 who:
24 a. leases property from a landowner, and
Req. No. 17207 Page 4

1 b. operates an energy storage resource on the property;
2 and
3 5. "Resource owner" means the entity having a majority equity
4 interest in the energy storage resource, including its respective
5 successors and assigns.
6 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
7 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 180.17 of Title 17, unless there
8 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
9 A. An energy storage resource shall comply with the following
10 minimum safety codes and standards for energy storage resource
11 equipment or facilities:
12 1. The International Fire Code (IFC), as adopted and amended by
13 the Oklahoma Uniform Building Code Commission, in effect at the time
14 a construction permit is applied for; and
15 2. Criteria described in the National Fire Protection
16 Association (NFPA) 855 2026 Standard for the Installation of
17 Stationary Energy Storage Systems.
18 Where a conflict exists between the requirements of the IFC, as
19 adopted and amended by the Oklahoma Uniform Building Code
20 Commission, and the NFPA 855 2026 edition, the provisions of the
21 NFPA 855 2026 edition shall take precedence. For an energy storage
22 resource with a nameplate capacity equal to or less than one (1)
23 megawatt, only the provisions of this subsection shall apply.
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 5

1 B. Before a construction permit is issued for an energy storage
2 resource, the entity responsible for fire inspection and primary
3 emergency response may require the resource owner to pay for an
4 independent, third-party engineer licensed in this state or other
5 consultant with appropriate expertise, to provide a written report
6 to the entity responsible for fire inspection and primary emergency
7 response and the resource owner determining:
8 1. Whether the energy storage resource, as proposed, complies
9 with subsection A of this section; and
10 2. To the extent the energy storage resource does not comply
11 with subsection A of this section, any appropriate actions to cure
12 such noncompliance in accordance with the NFPA 855 2026 edition.
13 C. Any resource owner that receives a lawful request pursuant
14 to subsection B of this section shall cooperate with the request.
15 Such cooperation shall include providing the engineer or consultant
16 with all necessary documents relating to the energy storage
17 resource's site layout, emergency operations plan, hazard mitigation
18 analysis, manufacturer specifications, product listings, including,
19 but not limited to, UL 9540 and UL 9540A reports, compliance with
20 the NFPA 855 2026 edition and other applicable referenced standards,
21 electrical drawings, monitoring procedures, and fire protection
22 system, as applicable to the proposed energy storage resource. If
23 the engineer or consultant identifies appropriate actions to cure
24 noncompliance under paragraph 2 of subsection B of this section, the
Req. No. 17207 Page 6

1 reso urce owner shall implement said appropriate actions before
2 commencement of operations.
3 D. Energy storage resources, other than energy storage systems
4 installed in one- and two-family dwellings as defined in the NFPA
5 855 2026 edition, in this state shall have and maintain, at an on-
6 site location accessible to local first responders, a site-specific
7 emergency operations plan. In accordance with the NFPA 855 2026
8 edition, the site-specific emergency operations plan shall identify:
9 1. Potential risks and hazards specific to the site;
10 2. Hazard mitigation measures;
11 3. Procedures for the safe shutdown, de-energizing, or
12 isolation of equipment and systems under emergency conditions,
13 including emergency procedures to be followed in case of fire;
14 4. Procedures for handling equipment damaged in a fire or other
15 emergency event;
16 5. Procedures and schedules for conducting drills using the
17 procedures listed under this subsection and documentation related to
18 the performance of the drills;
19 6. Procedures for communication between the operator of the
20 energy storage resource and first responders, including procedures
21 that facilitate communication between first responders and emergency
22 contacts for the resource operator; and
23
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 7

1 7. Emergency operations protocols to ensure safety during
2 critical events, including protocols that provide for the safety of
3 nearby residents, neighboring properties, and first responders.
4 E. Before commencement of operations, the resource owner shall
5 provide the site-specific emergency operations plan to the entity
6 responsible for fire inspection and primary emergency response.
7 F. Energy storage resource owners in this state shall offer to
8 local first responders, at no cost to the responders, education and
9 training regarding responding to an equipment failure incident at
10 the energy storage resource site. The training shall include:
11 1. Training on specific characteristics of the energy storage
12 resource technology;
13 2. Training on protecting first responders during incident
14 response;
15 3. Training on hazards commonly associated with incident
16 response;
17 4. Training on incident response protocols, including an
18 overview of the site-specific emergency operations plan developed
19 under subsection D of this section; and
20 5. An on-site review of the perimeter, major equipment, and
21 ingress and egress to the energy storage resource site.
22 G. Unless expressly authorized by law, political subdivisions
23 in this state shall not adopt, enforce, or maintain any rules,
24 regulations, codes, or standards that uniquely apply to energy
Req. No. 17207 Page 8

1 stor age resources other than those set forth in the Oklahoma Energy
2 Storage Resource Safety Act.
3 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
4 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 180.18 of Title 17, unless there
5 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
6 A. An energy storage resource agreement executed after the
7 effective date of this act shall provide that the grantee is
8 responsible for removing the grantee’s components of an energy
9 storage resource facility from the landowner's property and that the
10 grantee shall, in accordance with any other applicable laws or
11 regulations, safely perform the following:
12 1. Clear, clean, and remove from the property each energy
13 storage resource and associated transformers and substations;
14 2. For each foundation of an energy storage resource,
15 transformer, or substation installed in the ground:
16 a. clear, clean, and remove the foundation from the
17 ground to a depth of at least three (3) feet below the
18 surface grade of the land in which the foundation is
19 installed, and
20 b. ensure that each hole or cavity created in the ground
21 by the removal is filled with soil of the same type or
22 a similar type as the predominant soil found on the
23 property;
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 9

1 3. For each buried cable, including power, fiber-optic, and
2 communications cables, installed in the ground:
3 a. clear, clean, and remove the cable from the ground to
4 a depth of at least three (3) feet below the surface
5 grade of the land in which the cable is installed, and
6 b. ensure that each hole or cavity created in the ground
7 by the removal is filled with soil of the same type or
8 a similar type as the predominant soil found on the
9 property; and
10 4. Clear, clean, and remove from the property each overhead
11 power or communications line installed by the grantee on the
12 property at the request of the landowner.
13 B. The agreement shall provide that, at the request of the
14 landowner, the grantee shall:
15 1. Clear, clean, and remove each road constructed by the
16 grantee on the property; and
17 2. Ensure that each hole or cavity created in the ground by the
18 removal is filled with soil of the same type or a similar type as
19 the predominant soil found on the property.
20 C. The agreement shall provide that, at the request of the
21 landowner, if reasonable, the grantee shall:
22 1. Remove from the property all rocks over twelve (12) inches
23 in diameter excavated during the decommissioning or removal process;
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 10

1 2. Return the property to a tillable state using scarification,
2 V-rip, or disc methods, as appropriate; and
3 3. Ensure that:
4 a. each hole or cavity created in the ground by the
5 removal is filled with soil of the same type or a
6 similar type as the predominant soil found on the
7 property, and
8 b. the surface is returned as near as reasonably possible
9 to the same condition as before the grantee dug holes
10 or cavities, including by reseeding pastureland with
11 native grasses prescribed by an appropriate
12 governmental agency, if any. Noninvasive grasses
13 shall be allowed when reseeding native grasses is not
14 economically feasible.
15 D. The landowner shall make a request under subsection B or C
16 of this section not later than the one hundred eightieth day after
17 the later of:
18 1. The date on which the landowner receives from the grantee
19 via certified mail a copy of a notification of intent to suspend
20 operations filed with a grid operator indicating an intent to
21 permanently cease operations; or
22 2. The date the landowner receives written notice of intent to
23 decommission the energy storage resource from the grantee.
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 11

1 E. The provisions of this section shall only apply to energy
2 storage resource agreements executed after the effective date of
3 this act and shall have no effect on existing agreements.
4 SECTION 6. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 180.19 of Title 17, unless there
6 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 A. An energy storage resource agreement executed after
8 effective date of this act shall provide that the grantee obtain and
9 deliver to the landowner evidence of financial assurance that
10 conforms to the requirements of this section to secure the
11 performance of the grantee's obligation to remove the grantee's
12 energy storage resource facilities located on the landowner's
13 property as described by Section 5 of this act. Acceptable forms of
14 financial assurance include a parent company guaranty with a minimum
15 investment grade credit rating for the parent company issued by a
16 major domestic credit rating agency, a letter of credit, a bond, or
17 another form of financial assurance reasonably acceptable to the
18 landowner.
19 B. The amount of the financial assurance shall be at least
20 equal to the estimated amount by which the cost of removing the
21 energy storage resource facilities from the landowner's property and
22 restoring the property to as near as reasonably possible the
23 condition of the property as of the date the agreement begins
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 12

1 exce eds the salvage value of the facilities, less any portion of the
2 value of the facilities pledged to secure outstanding debt.
3 C. The agreement shall provide that:
4 1. The estimated cost of removing the energy storage resource
5 facilities from the landowner's property and restoring the property
6 to as near as reasonably possible the condition of the property as
7 of the date the agreement begins, and the estimated salvage value of
8 the energy storage resource facilities, shall be determined by an
9 independent, third-party professional engineer licensed in this
10 state;
11 2. The grantee shall deliver to the landowner an updated
12 estimate, prepared by an independent, third-party professional
13 engineer licensed in this state, of the cost of removal and the
14 salvage value:
15 a. on or before the tenth anniversary of commencement of
16 operations of the energy storage resource facility,
17 and
18 b. at least once every five (5) years thereafter for the
19 remainder of the term of the agreement; and
20 3. The grantee is responsible for ensuring that the amount of
21 the financial assurance remains sufficient to cover the amount
22 required by subsection B of this section, consistent with the
23 estimates required by this subsection.
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 13

1 D. The grantee is responsible for the costs of obtaining
2 financial assurance described by this section and costs of
3 determining the estimated removal costs and salvage value.
4 E. The agreement shall provide that, if the grantee fails to
5 fulfill the scope of decommissioning and removal work specified in
6 the agreement, the grantee shall deliver the financial assurance not
7 later than the earlier of:
8 1. The date the energy storage resource agreement is
9 terminated; or
10 2. The twentieth anniversary of the commencement of operations
11 of the energy storage resources located on the landowner's property,
12 unless the term of the agreement is extended.
13 F. The grantee may not cancel financial assurance before the
14 date the grantee has completed the grantee's obligation to remove
15 the grantee's energy storage resource facilities located on the
16 landowner's property in the manner provided by this act, unless the
17 grantee provides the landowner with replacement financial assurance
18 at the time of or before the cancellation. In the event of a
19 transfer of ownership of the grantee's energy storage resource
20 facilities, the financial security provided by the grantee shall
21 remain in place until the date evidence of replacement financial
22 security meeting the requirements of this act is provided to the
23 landowner by the transferee.
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 14

1 G. The provisions of this section shall only apply to energy
2 storage resource agreements executed after the effective date of
3 this act and shall have no effect on existing agreements.
4 SECTION 7. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 180.20 of Title 17, unless there
6 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 A. A provision of an energy storage resource agreement executed
8 after the effective date of the Oklahoma Energy Storage Resource
9 Safety Act that purports to waive a right or exempt a grantee from a
10 liability or duty established under the Oklahoma Energy Storage
11 Resource Safety Act is void and unenforceable, but the remainder of
12 the agreement shall remain enforceable.
13 B. A resource owner shall comply with the decommissioning
14 obligations set forth in the Oklahoma Energy Storage Resource Safety
15 Act. A landowner subject to an energy storage resource agreement is
16 expressly authorized to bring an action in district court for
17 injunctive relief to enforce compliance with this act.
18 C. The provisions of this section are not exclusive. The
19 remedies provided in this section are in addition to any other
20 procedures or remedies provided by other law. Failure to comply
21 with the Oklahoma Energy Storage Resource Safety Act does not impair
22 the validity or enforceability of any lease, easement, mortgage,
23 deed of trust, or other interest in real property.
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 15

1 SECTION 8. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 180.21 of Title 17, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. For energy storage resource facilities located in areas
5 where no recognized local authority having jurisdiction exists, and
6 where, as a result, any component of an energy storage resource
7 facility or the energy storage resource facility itself is subject
8 to inspections, plan reviews, or permits from the Office of the
9 Oklahoma State Fire Marshal, as provided in the codes adopted by the
10 Oklahoma Uniform Building Code Commission, the State Fire Marshal
11 Commission may establish a fee rate of no more than six cents
12 ($0.06) per square foot of surface physically occupied aboveground
13 by energy storage resource facility infrastructure. Such fee shall
14 be inclusive of all inspections, plan reviews, permit issuance, and
15 other review actions undertaken by the Office of the Oklahoma State
16 Fire Marshal in connection with the project, and the total fee shall
17 not exceed Five Hundred Thousand Dollars ($500,000.00) for any
18 individual energy storage resource facility. Nothing in this
19 section shall be construed to authorize the collection of fees
20 beyond said amount, except as otherwise provided by law. Where a
21 recognized local authority having jurisdiction exists, such local
22 authority is subject to the same fee limitations as the Office of
23 the Oklahoma State Fire Marshal established in this subsection.
24 B. Any fees collected pursuant to subsection A of this section
Req. No. 17207 Page 16

1 shal l be distributed as follows:
2 1. Seventy-five percent (75%) of such fees shall be
3 distributed to the local fire department providing primary fire
4 protection services to the jurisdiction where the facility is
5 located, within sixty (60) days of receipt. Funds distributed under
6 this paragraph shall be used solely for fire protection, fire
7 prevention, inspections, training, or emergency response activities
8 related to the facility; and
9 2. Twenty-five percent (25%) of such fees shall be distributed
10 to the permit issuing authority, whether the Office of the Oklahoma
11 State Fire Marshal or a recognized local authority having
12 jurisdiction, if delegated.
13 C. For purposes of this section, "recognized local authority
14 having jurisdiction" means a city, town, college, county, or fire
15 protection district that has been recognized by the Office of the
16 Oklahoma State Fire Marshal as the authority having jurisdiction for
17 permits, inspections, and enforcement under the adopted codes.
18 D. The Office of the Oklahoma State Fire Marshal or a local
19 authority having jurisdiction, where applicable, shall complete any
20 review subject to subsection A of this section as soon as
21 practicable, and in no event later than thirty (30) calendar days
22 following receipt of complete site plans. In the event the Office
23 of the Oklahoma State Fire Marshal does not complete its review
24
Req. No. 17207 Page 17

1 with in thirty (30) calendar days, any applicable permits and
2 certificates shall be deemed issued.
3 E. The State Fire Marshal Commission shall adopt rules as
4 necessary to implement the provisions of this section, pursuant to
5 Section 324.9 of Title 74 of the Oklahoma Statutes, including, but
6 not limited to, fee collection and distributions.
